The natural response of an RL circuit can be effectively described using the circuit depicted in Fig. 7.3. It is assumed that the independent current source produces a constant current of \( I_{s} \mathrm{~A} \) and that the switch has been closed for an extended period, which we will define more precisely later. For now, it signifies that all currents and voltages have stabilized at a constant value. Consequently, only constant, or dc, currents can exist in the circuit immediately before the switch is opened, and hence the inductor behaves as a short circuit ( \( L d i / d t=0 \) ) before the stored energy is released.

Since the inductor acts as a short circuit, the voltage across the inductive branch is zero, and no current flows through \( R_{0} \) or \( R \). Therefore, all the source current \( I_{s} \) is directed through the inductive branch. To determine the natural response, we need to find the voltage and current at the resistor terminals after the switch is opened, that is, after the source is disconnected and the inductor starts releasing energy. If we define \( t=0 \) as the moment the switch is opened, the task becomes finding \( v(t) \) and \( i(t) \) for \( t \geq 0 \). For \( t \geq 0 \), the circuit shown in Fig. 7.3 simplifies to the one shown in Fig. 7.4.

To derive the expression for the current, we apply Kirchhoff's voltage law to obtain an equation involving \( i, R \), and \( L \). Summing the voltages around the closed loop yields

$$
\begin{equation*}
L \frac{d i}{d t}+R i=0 \tag{7.1}
\end{equation*}
$$

This equation is known as a first-order ordinary differential equation because it contains terms involving the ordinary derivative of the unknown, that is, \( d i / d t \). The highest order derivative in the equation is 1, hence the term first-order.

We can further describe this equation by noting that the coefficients \( R \) and \( L \) are constants, meaning they are not functions of either the dependent variable \( i \) or the independent variable \( t \). Thus, the equation can also be characterized as an ordinary differential equation with constant coefficients.

To solve Eq. 7.1, we divide by \( L \), move the term involving \( i \) to the right-hand side, and then multiply both sides by a differential time \( d t \). This gives

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d i}{d t} d t=-\frac{R}{L} i d t \tag{7.2}
\end{equation*}
$$

Recognizing the left-hand side of Eq. 7.2 as a differential change in the current \( i \), we divide through by \( i \) to get

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d i}{i}=-\frac{R}{L} d t \tag{7.3}
\end{equation*}
$$

By integrating both sides of Eq. 7.3, we obtain an explicit expression for \( i \) as a function of \( t \). Using \( x \) and \( y \) as variables of integration leads to

$$
\begin{equation*}
\int_{i\left(t_{0}\right)}^{i(t)} \frac{d x}{x}=-\frac{R}{L} \int_{t_{0}}^{t} d y \tag{7.4}
\end{equation*}
$$

where \( i\left(t_{0}\right) \) is the current at time \( t_{0} \), and \( i(t) \) is the current at time \( t \). Here, \( t_{0}=0 \). Carrying out the integration yields

$$
\begin{equation*}
\ln \frac{i(t)}{i(0)}=-\frac{R}{L} t \tag{7.5}
\end{equation*}
$$

Based on the definition of the natural logarithm, we have

$$
\begin{equation*}
i(t)=i(0) e^{-(R / L) t} \tag{7.6}
\end{equation*}
$$

Recall that an instantaneous change of current cannot occur in an inductor. Therefore, in the first instant after the switch is opened, the current in the inductor remains the same. If we denote the time just before switching as \( 0^{-} \) and the time immediately after switching as \( 0^{+} \), then

$$
i\left(0^{-}\right)=i\left(0^{+}\right)=I_{0}
$$

where \( I_{0} \) represents the initial current in the inductor, as shown in Fig. 7.1. The initial current in the inductor flows in the same direction as the reference direction of \( i \). Thus, Eq. 7.6 becomes

$$
\begin{equation*}
i(t)=I_{0} e^{-(R / L) t}, \quad t \geq 0 \tag{7.7}
\end{equation*}
$$

indicating that the current starts from an initial value \( I_{0} \) and decreases exponentially towards zero as \( t \) increases. This behavior is illustrated in Fig. 7.5.

We derive the voltage across the resistor in Fig. 7.4 using Ohm's law:

$$
\begin{equation*}
v=i R=I_{0} R e^{-(R / L) t}, \quad t \geq 0^{+} \tag{7.8}
\end{equation*}
$$

Note that, unlike the expression for the current shown in Eq. 7.7, the voltage is defined only for \( t>0 \), not at \( t=0 \). The reason is that a step change occurs in the voltage at zero. For \( t<0 \), the derivative of the current is zero, so the voltage is also zero. (This follows from \( v=L d i / d t=0 \)). Therefore,

$$
\begin{align*}
& v\left(0^{-}\right)=0  \tag{7.9}\\
& v\left(0^{+}\right)=I_{0} R \tag{7.10}
\end{align*}
$$

where \( v\left(0^{+}\right) \) is obtained from Eq. 7.8 with \( t=0^{+} \). With this step change at an instant in time, the value of the voltage at \( t=0 \) is unknown. Thus, we use \( t \geq 0^{+} \) in defining the region of validity for these solutions.

We can derive the power dissipated in the resistor using any of the following expressions:

$$
\begin{equation*}
p=v i, \quad p=i^{2} R, \quad \text { or } \quad p=\frac{v^{2}}{R} \tag{7.11}
\end{equation*}
$$

Regardless of the form used, the resulting expression can be simplified to

$$
\begin{equation*}
p=I_{0}^{2} R e^{-2(R / L) t}, \quad t \geq 0^{+} \tag{7.12}
\end{equation*}
$$

The energy delivered to the resistor during any time interval after the switch is opened is

$$
\begin{align*}
w & =\int_{0}^{t} p d x=\int_{0}^{t} I_{0}^{2} R e^{-2(R / L) x} d x \\
& =\frac{1}{2(R / L)} I_{0}^{2} R\left(1-e^{-2(R / L) t}\right) \\
& =\frac{1}{2} L I_{0}^{2}\left(1-e^{-2(R / L) t}\right), \quad t \geq 0 \tag{7.13}
\end{align*}
$$

As \( t \) approaches infinity, the energy dissipated in the resistor approaches the initial energy stored in the inductor, as indicated by Eq. 7.13.

The expressions for \( i(t) \) (Eq. 7.7) and \( v(t) \) (Eq. 7.8) include a term of the form \( e^{-(R / L) t} \). The coefficient of \( t \)-namely, \( R / L \)-determines the rate at which the current or voltage approaches zero. The reciprocal of this ratio is the time constant of the circuit, denoted

$$
\begin{equation*}
\tau=\text { time constant }=\frac{L}{R} \tag{7.14}
\end{equation*}
$$

Using the time-constant concept, we can rewrite the expressions for current, voltage, power, and energy as

$$
\begin{align*}
i(t) & =I_{0} e^{-t / \tau}, \quad t \geq 0  \tag{7.15}\\
v(t) & =I_{0} R e^{-t / \tau}, \quad t \geq 0^{+}  \tag{7.16}\\
p & =I_{0}^{2} R e^{-2 t / \tau}, \quad t \geq 0^{+}  \tag{7.17}\\
w & =\frac{1}{2} L I_{0}^{2}\left(1-e^{-2 t / \tau}\right), \quad t \geq 0 \tag{7.18}
\end{align*}
$$

The time constant is a crucial parameter for first-order circuits. It is convenient to consider the time elapsed after switching in terms of integral multiples of \( \tau \). One time constant after the inductor starts releasing its stored energy to the resistor, the current has decreased to \( e^{-1} \), or approximately 0.37 of its initial value.

Table 7.1 provides the value of \( e^{-t / \tau} \) for integral multiples of \( \tau \) from 1 to 10. When the elapsed time exceeds five time constants, the current is less than 1% of its initial value. Thus, we often say that five time constants after switching has occurred, the currents and voltages have, for most practical purposes, reached their final values. For single time-constant circuits (first-order circuits) with 1% accuracy, the phrase "a long time" implies that five or more time constants have elapsed. Therefore, the existence of current in the RL circuit shown in Fig. 7.1(a) is a momentary event and is referred to as the transient response of the circuit. The response that exists a long time after the switching has taken place is called the steady-state response. The phrase "a long time" then also refers to the time it takes the circuit to reach its steady-state value.

Any first-order circuit is characterized, in part, by the value of its time constant. If we have no method for calculating the time constant of such a circuit (perhaps because we don't know the values of its components), we can determine its value from a plot of the circuit's natural response. Another important characteristic of the time constant is that it gives the time required for the current to reach its final value if the current continues to change at its initial rate. To illustrate, we evaluate \( d i / d t \) at \( 0^{+} \) and assume that the current continues to change at this rate:

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d i}{d t}\left(0^{+}\right)=-\frac{R}{L} I_{0}=-\frac{I_{0}}{\tau} \tag{7.19}
\end{equation*}
$$

Now, if \( i \) starts as \( I_{0} \) and decreases at a constant rate of \( I_{0} / \tau \) amperes per second, the expression for \( i \) becomes

$$
\begin{equation*}
i=I_{0}-\frac{I_{0}}{\tau} t . \tag{7.20}
\end{equation*}
$$

Equation 7.20 indicates that \( i \) would reach its final value of zero in \( \tau \) seconds. Figure 7.6 shows how this graphical interpretation is useful in estimating the time constant of a circuit from a plot of its natural response. Such a plot could be generated on an oscilloscope measuring output current. Drawing the tangent to the natural response plot at \( t=0 \) and reading the value at which the tangent intersects the time axis gives the value of \( \tau \).

Calculating the natural response of an RL circuit can be summarized as follows:

1. Determine the initial current \( I_{0} \) through the inductor.
2. Find the time constant of the circuit, \( \tau=L / R \).
3. Use Eq. 7.15, \( I_{0} e^{-t / \tau} \), to generate \( i(t) \) from \( I_{0} \) and \( \tau \).

All other calculations of interest follow from knowing \( i(t) \). Examples 7.1 and 7.2 demonstrate the numerical calculations associated with the natural response of an RL circuit.

Table 7.1 provides the value of \( e^{-t / \tau} \) for \( t \) equal to integral multiples of \( \tau \).

Figure 7.6 visually represents the natural response of an RL circuit, plotting current \( i \) on the vertical axis against time \( t \) on the horizontal axis. The graph is an exponential decay curve representing the current \( i(t) \) in an RL circuit after a switch has been opened, showing the behavior of the current over time as it decreases from its initial value \( I_0 \).

The graph is annotated with the exponential decay equation \( i = I_0 e^{-t/\tau} \) and its linear approximation \( i = I_0 - (I_0/\tau)t \).

The behavior of an RL circuit's natural response can be illuminated by examining the circuit illustrated in Fig. 7.3. Here, we postulate that a constant current $I_{s}$, in amperes, is produced by an independent current source, and the switch has remained closed for an extended period, a duration we will define more precisely later in this section. For now, it implies that the circuit's currents and voltages have stabilized at constant levels. Consequently, the circuit is characterized by direct current (dc) only immediately before the switch is opened, rendering the inductor indistinguishable from a short circuit $(L d i / d t=0)$ until the energy stored within is released.

Since the inductor behaves as a short circuit, the voltage across it is negligible, precluding any current flow through $R_{0}$ or $R$. Thus, the entire source current $I_{s}$ courses through the inductive branch. The task of determining the natural response involves ascertaining the voltage and current values at the resistor's terminals post-switch opening—i.e., after the source is disconnected and the inductor initiates energy release. If we denote the moment of switch opening as $t=0$, our challenge is to calculate $v(t)$ and $i(t)$ for all $t \geq 0$. Post-switch opening, the circuit depicted in Fig. 7.3 simplifies to that shown in Fig. 7.4.

Derivation of the Current Expression

To calculate $i(t)$, we apply Kirchhoff's voltage law to derive an equation relating $i$, $R$, and $L$. Summing voltages in the loop yields

$$
\begin{equation*}
L \frac{d i}{d t}+R i=0 \tag{7.1}
\end{equation*}
$$

This is according to the passive sign convention. Equation 7.1 is recognized as a first-order ordinary differential equation due to its inclusion of the unknown's ordinary derivative, $d i / d t$, with the highest derivative order being 1.

We can elaborate on this equation's nature. The coefficients $R$ and $L$ are constants, independent of the dependent variable $i$ or the independent variable $t$. Thus, the equation is also classified as an ordinary differential equation with constant coefficients.

To solve Equation 7.1, we divide by $L$, move the term involving $i$ to the right-hand side, and multiply both sides by $d t$. This leads to

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d i}{d t} d t=-\frac{R}{L} i d t \tag{7.2}
\end{equation*}
$$

Next, we acknowledge the left-hand side of Equation 7.2 as representing the differential change in current $i$, or $d i$. By dividing through by $i$, we obtain

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d i}{i}=-\frac{R}{L} d t \tag{7.3}
\end{equation*}
$$

We derive an explicit expression for $i$ as a function of $t$ by integrating both sides of Equation 7.3. Employing $x$ and $y$ as variables of integration gives

$$
\begin{equation*}
\int_{i\left(t_{0}\right)}^{i(t)} \frac{d x}{x}=-\frac{R}{L} \int_{t_{0}}^{t} d y \tag{7.4}
\end{equation*}
$$

Here, $i\left(t_{0}\right)$ represents the current at time $t_{0}$, while $i(t)$ is the current at time $t$. Given that $t_{0}=0$, performing the integration results in

$$
\begin{equation*}
\ln \frac{i(t)}{i(0)}=-\frac{R}{L} t \tag{7.5}
\end{equation*}
$$

Utilizing the natural logarithm's definition, we arrive at

$$
\begin{equation*}
i(t)=i(0) e^{-(R / L) t} \tag{7.6}
\end{equation*}
$$

As discussed in Chapter 6, an instantaneous current change cannot occur in an inductor. Hence, the instant following the switch's opening, the inductor's current remains unaltered. Denoting the moment just before switching as $0^{-}$ and the instant after as $0^{+}$, we have

$$
i\left(0^{-}\right)=i\left(0^{+}\right)=I_{0}
$$

Here, $I_{0}$ signifies the initial current in the inductor, aligning with the reference direction of $i$. Thus, Equation 7.6 is revised
