As outlined in Section 7.1, the inherent response of an RC circuit mirrors that of an RL circuit. Thus, we do not delve into the specifics of the RC circuit as meticulously as we did with the RL circuit.

The inherent response of an RC circuit can be derived from the configuration depicted in Fig. 7.10. Our analysis commences with the assumption that the switch has been in position 'a' for an extended period, enabling the loop composed of the DC voltage source \( V_g \), resistor \( R_1 \), and capacitor \( C \) to attain a steady state. As previously discussed in Chapter 6, a capacitor acts as an open circuit when subjected to a constant voltage. Consequently, the voltage source is unable to maintain a current, resulting in the voltage source's voltage being present across the capacitor terminals. In Section 7.3, we will explore how the capacitor voltage attains the steady-state value of the DC voltage source, but for the present discussion, the critical point is that when the switch is shifted from position 'a' to 'b' (at \( t=0 \)), the voltage across the capacitor is \( V_g \). Since there can be no instantaneous change in the voltage at the terminals of a capacitor, the task reduces to solving the circuit depicted in Fig. 7.11.

#V# Deriving the Expression for Voltage

We can effortlessly determine the voltage \( v(t) \) by considering node voltages. Designating the lower node between \( R \) and \( C \) as the reference node and summing the currents departing from the upper node between \( R \) and \( C \) yields

$$
\begin{equation*}
C \frac{d v}{d t}+\frac{v}{R}=0 \tag{7.21}
\end{equation*}
$$

A comparison of Eq. 7.21 with Eq. 7.1 reveals that the same mathematical methods can be employed to derive the solution for \( v(t) \). It is left to the reader to demonstrate that

$$
\begin{equation*}
v(t)=v(0) e^{-t / R C}, \quad t \geq 0 \tag{7.22}
\end{equation*}
$$

As previously noted, the initial voltage across the capacitor is equivalent to the voltage source voltage \( V_g \), or

$$
\begin{equation*}
v\left(0^{-}\right)=v(0)=v\left(0^{+}\right)=V_{g}=V_{0}, \tag{7.23}
\end{equation*}
$$

where \( V_{0} \) represents the initial voltage across the capacitor. The time constant for the RC circuit is the product of the resistance and capacitance, given by

$$
\begin{equation*}
\tau=R C \tag{7.24}
\end{equation*}
$$

Substituting Eqs. 7.23 and 7.24 into Eq. 7.22 results in

$$
\begin{equation*}
v(t)=V_{0} e^{-t / \tau}, \quad t \geq 0 \tag{7.25}
\end{equation*}
$$

indicating that the inherent response of an RC circuit is an exponential decay of the initial voltage. The time constant \( RC \) governs the decay rate. Figure 7.12 illustrates the plot of Eq. 7.25 and provides a graphical interpretation of the time constant.

With \( v(t) \) established, we can readily derive the expressions for \( i, p \), and \( w \) :

$$
\begin{align*}
i(t) & =\frac{v(t)}{R}=\frac{V_{0}}{R} e^{-t / \tau}, \quad t \geq 0^{+}  \tag{7.26}\\
p & =v i=\frac{V_{0}^{2}}{R} e^{-2 t / \tau}, \quad t \geq 0^{+}  \tag{7.27}\\
w & =\int_{0}^{t} p d x=\int_{0}^{t} \frac{V_{0}^{2}}{R} e^{-2 x / \tau} d x \\
& =\frac{1}{2} C V_{0}^{2}\left(1-e^{-2 t / \tau}\right), \quad t \geq 0 \tag{7.28}
\end{align*}
$$

