We are now prepared to explore the challenge of determining the currents and voltages produced in first-order RL or RC circuits when a constant voltage or current source is abruptly introduced. The reaction of a circuit to the abrupt introduction of a constant voltage or current source is known as the step response. In our explanation of the step response, we demonstrate how the circuit behaves when energy is accumulated in the inductor or capacitor. We initiate with the step response of an RL circuit.

The Step Response of an RL Circuit

Initially, we alter the first-order circuit depicted in Fig. 7.2(a) by incorporating a switch. We employ the resulting circuit, displayed in Fig. 7.16, in our discussion of the step response of an RL circuit. The energy stored in the inductor at the moment the switch is activated is quantified by a nonzero initial current i(0). Our objective is to establish the expressions for the current within the circuit and the voltage across the inductor following the closure of the switch. The methodology remains the same as that outlined in Section 7.1; we employ circuit analysis to derive the differential equation that portrays the circuit in terms of the variable of interest, and subsequently, we apply basic calculus to solve the equation.

Once the switch in Fig. 7.16 is closed, Kirchhoff's voltage law necessitates that

$$
\begin{equation*}
V_{s}=R i+L \frac{d i}{d t} \tag{7.29}
\end{equation*}
$$

which can be resolved for the current by segregating the variables i and t and then integrating. The initial step in this process is to solve Eq. 7.29 for the derivative d i / d t :

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d i}{d t}=\frac{-R i+V_{s}}{L}=\frac{-R}{L}\left(i-\frac{V_{s}}{R}\right) \tag{7.30}
\end{equation*}
$$

Next, we multiply both sides of Eq. 7.30 by a differential time d t. This action simplifies the left-hand side of the equation to a differential adjustment in the current. Thus

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d i}{d t} d t=\frac{-R}{L}\left(i-\frac{V_{s}}{R}\right) d t \tag{7.31}
\end{equation*}
$$

or

$$
d i=\frac{-R}{L}\left(i-\frac{V_{s}}{R}\right) d t
$$

We now isolate the variables in Eq. 7.31 to obtain

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d i}{i-\left(V_{s} / R\right)}=\frac{-R}{L} d t \tag{7.32}
\end{equation*}
$$

and then integrate both sides of Eq. 7.32. Utilizing x and y as variables for the integration, we derive

$$
\begin{equation*}
\int_{I_{0}}^{i(t)} \frac{d x}{x-\left(V_{s} / R\right)}=\frac{-R}{L} \int_{0}^{t} d y \tag{7.33}
\end{equation*}
$$

where I_{0} represents the current at t=0 and i(t) denotes the current at any t>0. The integration called for in Eq. 7.33 yields the expression

$$
\begin{equation*}
\ln \frac{i(t)-\left(V_{s} / R\right)}{I_{0}-\left(V_{s} / R\right)}=\frac{-R}{L} t \tag{7.34}
\end{equation*}
$$

from which

$$
\frac{i(t)-\left(V_{s} / R\right)}{I_{0}-\left(V_{s} / R\right)}=e^{-(R / L) t}
$$

or

$$
\begin{equation*}
i(t)=\frac{V_{s}}{R}+\left(I_{0}-\frac{V_{s}}{R}\right) e^{-(R / L) t} \tag{7.35}
\end{equation*}
$$

Step response of RL circuit

When the initial energy in the inductor is negligible, I_{0} is zero. Hence, Eq. 7.35 simplifies to

$$
\begin{equation*}
i(t)=\frac{V_{s}}{R}-\frac{V_{s}}{R} e^{-(R / L) t} \tag{7.36}
\end{equation*}
$$

