If the current were to persist in increasing at this rate, the expression for i would be

$$
\begin{equation*}
i=\frac{V_{s}}{L} t \tag{7.40}
\end{equation*}
$$

from which, at t=τ,

$$
\begin{equation*}
i=\frac{V_{s}}{L} \frac{L}{R}=\frac{V_{s}}{R} \tag{7.41}
\end{equation*}
$$

Equations 7.36 and 7.40 are plotted in Fig. 7.17. The values provided by Eqs. 7.37 and 7.41 are also depicted in this figure.

The voltage across an inductor is L d i / d t, so from Eq. 7.35, for t ≥ 0^{+},

$$
\begin{equation*}
v=L\left(\frac{-R}{L}\right)\left(I_{0}-\frac{V_{s}}{R}\right) e^{-(R / L) t}=\left(V_{s}-I_{0} R\right) e^{-(R / L) t} \tag{7.42}
\end{equation*}
$$

The voltage across the inductor is zero prior to the switch being closed. Equation 7.42 indicates that the inductor voltage surges to V_{s}-I_{0} R at the instant the switch is closed and then decays exponentially to zero.

Does the value of v at t=0^{+} make sense? Because the initial current is I_{0} and the inductor inhibits an instantaneous change in current, the current is I_{0} in the instant after the switch is closed. The voltage drop across the resistor is I_{0} R, and the voltage impressed across the inductor is the source voltage minus the voltage drop, that is, V_{s}-I_{0} R.

When the initial inductor current is zero, Eq. 7.42 simplifies to

$$
\begin{equation*}
v=V_{s} e^{-(R / L) t} \tag{7.43}
\end{equation*}
$$

If the initial current is zero, the voltage across the inductor surges to V_{s}. We also anticipate the inductor voltage to approach zero as t increases, because the current in the circuit is approaching the constant value of V_{s} / R. Figure 7.18 exhibits the plot of Eq. 7.43 and the relationship between the time constant and the initial rate at which the inductor voltage is diminishing.

If there is an initial current in the inductor, Eq. 7.35 provides the solution for it. The algebraic sign of I_{0} is positive if the initial current is in the same direction as i; otherwise, I_{0} carries a negative sign. Example 7.5 exemplifies the application of Eq. 7.35 to a specific circuit.

#### Example 7.5 Determining the Step Response of an RL Circuit

The switch in the circuit depicted in Fig. 7.19 has been in position a for an extended duration. At t=0, the switch transitions from position a to position b. The switch is a make-before-break type; that is, the connection at position b is established before the connection at position a is severed, ensuring no disruption of current through the inductor.
a) Determine the expression for i(t) for t ≥ 0.
b) What is the initial voltage across the inductor immediately after the switch transitions to position b?
c) How many milliseconds after the switch transitions does the inductor voltage equal 24 V?
