7.5 Assume that the switch in the circuit depicted

We are now set to delve into the challenge of calculating the currents and voltages that emerge in first-order \( RL \) and \( RC \) circuits upon the abrupt application of either a DC voltage or current source. This reaction of the circuit to the sudden introduction of a constant voltage or current is known as the step response. In illustrating the step response, we demonstrate how the circuit behaves as energy is accumulated within the inductor or capacitor. We initiate our exploration with the step response of an \( RL \) circuit.

### The Step Response of an RL Circuit

Our initial step is to adapt the first-order circuit depicted in Fig. 7.2(a) by incorporating a switch. This modified circuit, as shown in Fig. 7.16, serves as the foundation for our analysis of the step response of an \( RL \) circuit. The energy stored within the inductor at the moment the switch is activated is characterized by a non-zero initial current \( i(0) \). Our goal is to derive expressions for the current flowing through the circuit and the voltage across the inductor subsequent to the closure of the switch. The methodology we employ is consistent with that outlined in Section 7.1; we leverage circuit analysis to formulate the differential equation that encapsulates the circuit's behavior with respect to the variable of interest, subsequently resolving the equation via elementary calculus.

Once the switch in Fig. 7.16 is activated, Kirchhoff's voltage law necessitates that

$$
\begin{equation*}
V_{s}=R i+L \frac{d i}{d t} \tag{7.29}
\end{equation*}
$$

This equation can be solved for the current by separating the variables \( i \) and \( t \) and subsequently integrating. The initial phase in this approach involves solving Eq. 7.29 for the derivative \( \frac{d i}{d t} \):

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d i}{d t}=\frac{-R i+V_{s}}{L}=\frac{-R}{L}\left(i-\frac{V_{s}}{R}\right) \tag{7.30}
\end{equation*}
$$

Subsequently, we multiply both sides of Eq. 7.30 by a differential time \( d t \). This step simplifies the left-hand side of the equation to a differential change in the current. Therefore,

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d i}{d t} d t=\frac{-R}{L}\left(i-\frac{V_{s}}{R}\right) d t \tag{7.31}
\end{equation*}
$$

or

$$
d i=\frac{-R}{L}\left(i-\frac{V_{s}}{R}\right) d t
$$

We proceed to separate the variables in Eq. 7.31 to obtain

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d i}{i-\left(V_{s} / R\right)}=\frac{-R}{L} d t \tag{7.32}
\end{equation*}
$$

Upon integrating both sides of Eq. 7.32, using \( x \) and \( y \) as variables for the integration, we arrive at

$$
\begin{equation*}
\int_{I_{0}}^{i(t)} \frac{d x}{x-\left(V_{s} / R\right)}=\frac{-R}{L} \int_{0}^{t} d y \tag{7.33}
\end{equation*}
$$

Here, \( I_{0} \) represents the current at \( t=0 \), and \( i(t) \) denotes the current at any \( t>0 \). The integration process outlined in Eq. 7.33 yields the expression

$$
\begin{equation*}
\ln \frac{i(t)-\left(V_{s} / R\right)}{I_{0}-\left(V_{s} / R\right)}=\frac{-R}{L} t \tag{7.34}
\end{equation*}
$$

from which we derive

$$
\frac{i(t)-\left(V_{s} / R\right)}{I_{0}-\left(V_{s} / R\right)}=e^{-(R / L) t}
$$

or

$$
\begin{equation*}
i(t)=\frac{V_{s}}{R}+\left(I_{0}-\frac{V_{s}}{R}\right) e^{-(R / L) t} \tag{7.35}
\end{equation*}
$$

### Step Response of RL Circuit

When the initial energy in the inductor is negligible, \( I_{0} \) is zero. Thus, Eq. 7.35 simplifies to

$$
\begin{equation*}
i(t)=\frac{V_{s}}{R}-\frac{V_{s}}{R} e^{-(R / L) t} \tag{7.36}
\end{equation*}
$$

This equation reveals that following the activation of the switch, the current exhibits an exponential rise from zero, asymptotically approaching a final value of \( \frac{V_{s}}{R} \). The time constant of the circuit, \( L/R \), governs the rate of this increase. After a period equivalent to one time constant, the current will have achieved approximately \( 63\% \) of its ultimate value, or

$$
\begin{equation*}
i(\tau)=\frac{V_{s}}{R}-\frac{V_{s}}{R} e^{-1} \approx 0.6321 \frac{V_{s}}{R} \tag{7.37}
\end{equation*}
$$

If the current were to sustain its initial rate of increase, it would attain its final value at \( t=\tau \); that is, because

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d i}{d t}=\frac{-V_{s}}{R}\left(\frac{-1}{\tau}\right) e^{-t / \tau}=\frac{V_{s}}{L} e^{-t / \tau} \tag{7.38}
\end{equation*}
$$

the initial rate of increase of \( i(t) \) is

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d i}{d t}(0)=\frac{V_{s}}{L} \tag{7.39}
\end{equation*}
$$

Should the current continue to increase at this rate, the expression for \( i \) would be

$$
\begin{equation*}
i=\frac{V_{s}}{L} t \tag{7.40}
\end{equation*}
$$

from which, at \( t=\tau \),

$$
\begin{equation*}
i=\frac{V_{s}}{L} \frac{L}{R}=\frac{V_{s}}{R} \tag{7.41}
\end{equation*}
$$

Equations 7.36 and 7.40 are illustrated in Fig. 7.17. The values derived from Eqs. 7.37 and 7.41 are also depicted in this figure.

Given that the voltage across an inductor is \( L \frac{d i}{d t} \), from Eq. 7.35, for \( t \geq 0^{+} \),

$$
\begin{equation*}
v=L\left(\frac{-R}{L}\right)\left(I_{0}-\frac{V_{s}}{R}\right) e^{-(R / L) t}=\left(V_{s}-I_{0} R\right) e^{-(R / L) t} \tag{7.42}
\end{equation*}
$$

The voltage across the inductor is negligible before the switch is activated. Eq. 7.42 indicates that the inductor voltage surges to \( V_{s}-I_{0} R \) at the instant the switch is closed and then undergoes exponential decay towards zero.

The initial voltage \( v \) at \( t=0^{+} \) aligns with our expectations because the initial current is \( I_{0} \), and the inductor opposes any instantaneous change in current. Consequently, the current remains \( I_{0} \) in the instant following the closure of the switch. The voltage drop across the resistor is \( I_{0} R \), and the voltage induced across the inductor is the source voltage minus the voltage drop, i.e., \( V_{s}-I_{0} R \).

In the scenario where the initial inductor current is zero, Eq. 7.42 simplifies to

$$
\begin{equation*}
v=V_{s} e^{-(R / L) t} \tag{7.43}
\end{equation*}
$$

When the initial current is zero, the voltage across the inductor spikes to \( V_{s} \). We also anticipate that the inductor voltage will diminish towards zero as \( t \) increases, since the current in the circuit is approaching the constant value of \( V_{s} / R \). Figure 7.18 presents the plot of Eq. 7.43 and elucidates the relationship between the time constant and the initial rate of decrease of the inductor voltage.

If an initial current is present in the inductor, Eq. 7.35 provides the solution. The algebraic sign of \( I_{0} \) is positive if the initial current aligns with the direction of \( i \); otherwise, \( I_{0} \) assumes a negative sign. Example 7.5 showcases the application of Eq. 7.35 to a specific circuit.

#### Example 7.5 Determining the Step Response of an RL Circuit

The switch in the circuit depicted in Fig. 7.19 has been in position 'a' for an extended duration. At \( t=0 \), the switch transitions from position 'a' to position 'b'. This switch is of the make-before-break type; hence, the connection at position 'b' is established prior to the disconnection at position 'a', ensuring uninterrupted current flow through the inductor.
a) Determine the expression for \( i(t) \) for \( t \geq 0 \).
b) Calculate the initial voltage across the inductor immediately following the switch's movement to position 'b'.
c) Determine the time, in milliseconds, required for the inductor voltage to reach 24 V after the switch has been shifted.
d) Assess whether this initial voltage is consistent with the expected circuit behavior.
e) Plot both \( i(t) \) and \( v(t) \) versus \( t \).

The circuit in Fig. 7.19 features a switch SW1 that alters its position at \( t=0 \), modifying the current path through the inductor L1. Initially, the inductor current is 8 A, opposing the reference direction for \( i \). The final current value is 12 A, with a time constant of 100 ms.

#### Solution

a) With the switch positioned at 'a' for a prolonged period, the 200 mH inductor behaves as a short circuit across the 8 A current source. Consequently, the inductor sustains an initial current of 8 A. This current is oriented opposite to the reference direction for \( i \); hence, \( I_{0} \) is -8 A. When the switch is in position 'b', the final value of \( i \) will be \( 24 / 2 \) or 12 A. The time constant of the circuit is \( 200 / 2 \) or 100 ms. Substituting these values into Eq. 7.35 yields

$$
\begin{aligned}
i & =12+(-8-12) e^{-t / 0.1} \\
& =12-20 e^{-10 t} \mathrm{~A}, \quad t \geq 0
\end{aligned}
$$

b) The voltage across the inductor is

$$
\begin{aligned}
v & =L \frac{d i}{d t} \\
& =0.2\left(200 e^{-10 t}\right) \\
& =40 e^{-10 t} \mathrm{~V}, \quad t \geq 0^{+}
\end{aligned}
$$

The initial inductor voltage is

$$
v\left(0^{+}\right)=40 \mathrm{~V}
$$

c) Yes; immediately after the switch is moved to position 'b', the inductor maintains a current of 8 A, flowing counterclockwise around the newly formed closed path. This current generates a 16 V drop across the \( 2 \Omega \) resistor. This voltage drop combines with the source voltage, resulting in a 40 V drop across the inductor.
d) To find the time at which the inductor voltage equals 24 V, we solve the equation

$$
24=40 e^{-10 t}
$$

for \( t \):

$$
\begin{aligned}
t & =\frac{1}{10} \ln \frac{40}{24} \\
& =51.08 \times 10^{-3} \\
& =51.08 \mathrm{~ms} .
\end{aligned}
$$

e) Figure 7.20 exhibits the graphs of \( i(t) \) and \( v(t) \) versus \( t \). Note that the instance when the current equals zero corresponds to the moment when the inductor voltage equals the source voltage of 24 V, as predicted by Kirchhoff's voltage law.

The graph in Figure 7.20 depicts the time-domain waveforms illustrating the behavior of current \( i(t) \) and voltage \( v(t) \) across an inductor over time \( t \), measured in milliseconds (ms). The horizontal axis represents time, ranging from 0 to 500 ms, while the vertical axis features two scales: voltage \( v \) in volts (V) on the left, and current \( i \) in amperes (A) on the right.

The voltage \( v(t) \), depicted by the black curve, commences at 40 V at \( t = 0 \) and exhibits an exponential decay towards zero as time progresses. Notably, the voltage reaches 24 V at approximately 51.08 ms, which aligns with the calculated time when the inductor voltage equals the source voltage.

The current \( i(t) \), represented by the blue curve, begins at -8 A at \( t = 0 \) and increases exponentially towards zero as time increases. This behavior is consistent with the step response of an RL circuit, where the current eventually stabilizes.

Key features include the zero-crossing point of the current, which coincides with the voltage reaching the source voltage of 24 V, as predicted by Kirchhoff's voltage law. The graph visually demonstrates the transient response of an RL circuit, highlighting the interplay between voltage and current over time.

